2 Exercise 1

  1. Calculate for each clarity-group of the diamonds the min, max, median and standard deviation of price. The column names are price_median, price_min, price_max, and price_sd.

  2. Which clarity refers to the highest median price? (Use the result from a) and calculate this result with filtering. Hint: check out function which.max(). It might help)

# a)
diamonds_clarity_price <- diamonds %>% 
  group_by(clarity) %>% 
  summarise(price_median = median(price),
            price_min = min(price),
            price_max = max(price),
            price_sd = sd(price))

# b)
diamonds_clarity_price$clarity[which.max(diamonds_clarity_price$price_median)]
## [1] SI2
## Levels: I1 < SI2 < SI1 < VS2 < VS1 < VVS2 < VVS1 < IF

3 Exercise 2

Calculate an additional variable in the dataframe diamonds, called outer_volume, which is the product of x, y, and z.

diamonds <- diamonds %>% 
  mutate (outer_volume = x * y * z)

4 Exercise 3

You will create a plot, that is modified and extended in each sub-task.

  1. Create a scatter-plot with ggplot2, showing price vs. outer_volume.

  2. Find out how you can show only a zoomed area and show only data in the range of outer_volume of 0 to 600 mm^3.

  3. Find out how to modify x- and y-labels and rename x-label Outer Volume [mm^3] and y-label Price [$]

  4. Find out how to define a plot-title and use the title Diamonds: Price and Outer Volume

  5. Besides x and y-variable, also color can be used as additional dimension for plotting. Find out how to plot each points color with reference to its clarity.

g <- ggplot (diamonds, aes(x = outer_volume, y = price, col = clarity))
g <- g + geom_point(alpha = .1)
g <- g + coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 600))
g <- g + xlab ("Outer Volume [mm^3]")
g <- g + ylab ("Price [$]")
g <- g + ggtitle ("Diamonds: Price and Outer Volume")
g

5 Exercise 4

  1. Create a filtered dataset, called diamonds_filt, which filters data for

  • outer_volume > 0

  • price between 500 and 15000 $.

  1. Calculate the filter-ratio in percentage (nr. of kept observations in filtered vs.original (unfiltered) dataset)?
diamonds_filt <- diamonds %>% 
  filter (outer_volume > 0) %>% 
  filter (price > 500 & price < 15000)

filter_ratio <- nrow(diamonds_filt) / nrow(diamonds) * 100
